The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, June 18, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Ramco Systems Ltd, a software firm, has registered a net profit of Rs 4.20 crore in the last quarter of 2003-04 compared with a loss of Rs 3.34 crore in the year-ago period. However, in 2003-04, the companys losses stood at Rs 33.26 crore compared with Rs 27.32 crore in 2002-03. Vice-president and managing director P. R. Venketrama Raja said the companys solution assembly and delivery platform, Ramco Virtualworks, has been successfully delivered and this will drive growth this fiscal.																								 Hughes Software Systems has been selected by an Italian alternative broadband telecom company, e.Biscoms Fastweb, to increase the VOIP capability of its triple-play integrated network. Fastweb provides VOIP to business and residential customers. 																								 Union Bank of India has increased interest rates for its FCNR(B) term deposits by 0.21-0.23 per cent for various maturities with effect from June 18. The revised rates for dollar deposits for one year to less than two years, two years to less than three years and three years are 2.18 per cent (1.95 per cent), 3 per cent (2.77 per cent) and 3.55 per cent (3.34 per cent), respectively. 																								 Hindustan Zinc Ltd has posted a 184.52 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 404.6 crore for the fiscal ended March 31, 2004 compared with Rs 142.2 crore in the previous year. The board has recommended a dividend of 14 per cent, the company informed the stock exchange.																								 Aptech Ltd, an IT education major, has posted a 32 per cent rise in revenues from international operations at $3.76 million in May 2004 against $2.84 million in the year-ago period. The rise in revenues is due to an impressive growth from countries like Turkey, Vietnam and China, Aptech said. 																								 Export-Import Bank of India (Exim Bank) has signed a line of credit agreement with Uniao de Bancos Brasileiros (Unibanco), a Brazilian private sector bank, for a credit of $10 million to finance Indias export of equipment. 																								 Ford Motor India has sold over 10,000 Ikon models in the first five months of this year and the company is poised to post profit in 2004. Cumulative (January-May) sales of Ikon went up by 52 per cent over the same period last financial year.																								 Hindustan Motors has launched an upgraded range of the Lancer model which would be offered along with a three-year or 50,000 km warranty. The four new Lancer models have been priced between Rs 7.25 lakh and Rs 9.77 lakh (ex-showroom, Delhi), chief general manager S. C. Gupta said.																								 Apollo Tyres will forge a multi-brand distribution initiative with Michelin to provide a wider variety of passenger car tyres, the company stated in a release. ADVERTISEMENT
